metadata.name: A Gift of Nature #141
metadata.description:
Can nature really be a gift if it isn't ours to give?
Do we feel the need to bind it close in the ways of old to live?
If a gift was given would all be forgiven, a place of harmony now we can live in?

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

A gift of nature, sort of. As natural as a digital gift can be. It is a gen art token of my gratitude you might say. It is the younger sibling of "The Spectrum of Nature". 

This is a gift from me to you, a gift of nature that pulls you through. 

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article “The spectrum of nature - a short making of”. However, feel free to skip the article.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Basic info:
The initial render will be 1000px wide and 1000px high. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that’s present.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x2000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x9000 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won’t need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there.

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

metadata.name: Circonvolution #50
metadata.description:
Circonvolution is a French word meaning "wrapped around" but also "twists and turns".
In this project, several vortexes drive colors in a chaotic winding path whose final look is sometimes quite organic.

Depending on the computer, the calculation time may be about ten seconds.
---
To save, type:
[1] at 2000x2000 px
To save in high resolution, (can be long)
[2] at 4000x6000 px 
[3] at 6000x6000 px

---

100% done with p5js
Some colors are from "A Dictionary of Color Combinations" by Wada Sanzō
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

Hervé (Jan 23)

metadata.name: Life has no scores #124
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop “Nothing comes from nothing”. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press ‘2’ to save png.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #577
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Vulvator #34
metadata.description:
A Collaboration of illustrator and artist Ma-Ka (Martta-Kaisa Virta) and artist Antti Pussinen.
The body-positive artwork explores the diversity and beauty of the vulva.
Instead of anatomic correctness, Ma-Ka tries to capture the the idea and aesthetic philosophy of the Origin of us all. 

There are at least 1632960 different illustration combinations + hash generated colors, backgrounds and textures.

All of them are rare and unique, so no trackable features.

Illustrations and concept by Ma-Ka, Code, colors and textures by Antti Pussinen.
All profits will be split 50/50 by the artists. 

More illustrations from Ma-Ka @
http://makaflux.com/
https://www.instagram.com/makavirta/

metadata.name: Inefficient Ways of Independence #88
metadata.description:
"Inefficient Ways of Independence" is a thought - provoking artwork that explores the relationship between technology and the human experience.

The piece features a collection of iconic symbols of old technology, such as closed - circuit TV cameras, floppy disks, and vintage Mac computers, coupled together by a flow of particles.

The use of human body parts or heads adds a personal touch to the work, highlighting the intimate connection between the individual and technology.

The title "Inefficient Ways of Independence" serves as a commentary on our dependence on technology and the way that it has changed over time.

It also raises questions about our relationship with technology and the limitations that it can impose.

The piece invites the viewer to consider how technology has shaped our lives and to reflect on the consequences of our reliance on it.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT

metadata.name: The Fable #18
metadata.description:
In the collaborative project for The Fable, Kristen and Iofeye are exploring questions and themes in the space where human-technology-nature intersect. Based on AI generated fable-like creatures and fictional language, combined with intuitively created analog signs as well as sound, they are playing with the idea of telling possible stories about these creatures through different unpredictable generative results. More than a predetermined story, the project is a kind of a contemplation and a question about the crucial role of language, story and imagination in our relationship to the natural world around us and the technology that we develop and engage with.


Kristen Applegate
https://kristenapplegate.crevado.com/ 

As an artist, I am inspired by the intersection of technology and traditional craftsmanship. My work often uses humor to make playful yet thought-provoking statements about the consumption of animals, insects, and even humans as food. Recently this exploration has taken the form of creating AI images that become actual or projected surface decoration for pieces of ceramic dinnerware. Prompt-crafting with AI interfaces such as Midjourney and DALL-E allows me to create the odd animal-like storybook characters as well as the imaginative renderings of meat that appear in my work. My “anti-tale” characters are depicted in a vintage style that adds an element of nostalgia.
For our Floor project, Iofeye and I are delving further into the notion of storytelling using the extra anti-tale characters who did not make the cast list for my ceramic work. In this project, they get to tell their own stories in their own languages. I'm excited to hear what they say.


Indira Iofeye
https://linktr.ee/iofeye

My art is characterised by experimentation, exploration and intuitive expression and I am drawn to the potential that lies in collisions and connections between different media, expressive formats and conceptual universes. I am fascinated by the hybrid creations, by unlikely collisions and combinations, unpredictable turns and “mistakes”. For me, art and the artistic process are not solely about expressing something that already exists or is known, but also a way to ask and address questions about multiple aspects of existence, self, world and our relationships to different phenomena. It is also about opening up to a discovery and the encounter with the unknown inside oneself and the world through the creative process.

Some of the themes that I have worked with and that occupy me are storytelling by different means, the role of myth and the phenomenon of language, its role in our self-imaginary and our relationship to it.

The combination, the intersection and the synthesis of different themes, concepts and modalities of work that Kristen and I have brought into the project has given rise to a really engaging and interesting collaborative process and generated new fascinating avenues of possible explorations and discovery.

--

This token is part of The Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

metadata.name: The Vibesynth #15
metadata.description:
"The Vibesynth" is a unique collection of generative art that explores a captivating blend of dynamic digital styles, featuring retro-futuristic aesthetics, layered imagery, and a mesmerizing interplay of light, shadow and colour. Inspired by modern glitch art, synth-wave retro, 8-bit console gaming, and the mysteries of anonymity, each piece takes the viewer on a journey through an abstract and evocative world of shifting patterns and hypnotic vibes.

The art in this collection pushes the boundaries of contemporary art, using digital techniques to create stunning and dynamic representations of the interplay between technology and humanity. The glitch and distortion effects are not just a technical malfunction but rather an intentional exploration of the unexpected and the unpredictable. The synth-wave retro elements bring a sense of nostalgia and familiarity, while the console gaming aesthetics add a playful and dynamic energy to the collection. The anonymity of the art adds an element of mystery and intrigue, inviting the viewer to interpret each piece through their own lens.

Each piece is a unique and thought-provoking exploration of the human experience, inviting the viewer to get lost in the intricate and mesmerizing world of "The Vibesynth". This collection is a celebration of the power of generative art to evoke emotion and spark the imagination and a testament to the enduring power of art to shape our lives.

Press [S] to save the image.

Stas Kulesh aka gmi.sh and mentalnoise_e
Feb 2023

--

This token is part of The Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.
